12.10	Hanpen	Hanpen	Hanpen ) is a white, square, triangle or round shaped surimi product with a soft, mild taste. It is believed to have been invented during the Edo period in Japan by a cook, Hanpei ) of Suruga, and the dish is named after him. Another theory suggests that because it is triangle shaped and appears to have been cut in half from a square, it is a half han) piece pen). It can be eaten as an ingredient in oden or soup. It can also be fried or broiled.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e4/Hanpen_by_yoppy.jpg/220px-Hanpen_by_yoppy.jpg
